quran[11]{c,v,t}:
  31,1,"Alif Lām Mīm."
  31,2,"These are the signs of the Wise Scripture,"
  31,3,"a guidance and a mercy for those who excel in doing good:"
  31,4,"those who establish the prayer and bring{1}the purifying charity{2}and of the Hereafter they are certain.",footnotes:1:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|2:The Arabic word used is zakāt, which denotes purification and growth.
  31,5,"Those are rightly guided by their Lord, and those are the successful."
  31,6,"And among mankind is one who trades in distracting tales to <span class=""h"">make</span><i class=""s"">(people) </i><span class=""h"">stray<sup foot_note=""80834"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span>from the way of Allah without knowledge, and to <span class=""h"">take it<sup foot_note=""80835"" class=""qiraat"">2</sup> </span>for a mockery; for those is a demeaning punishment."
  31,7,"And when Our signs{1}are recited to him, he turns away arrogantly as though he did not hear them, as though there is deafness in his ears. So give<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>him glad tidings{2}of a painful punishment.",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used isayat(singularayah). Ayahmeans ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an,like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose.Each such unit isconsidered a ‘sign’from God.|2:This is said in sarcasm.
  31,8,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—for them are the Gardens of Bliss,"
  31,9,"abiding therein, a true promise of Allah. And He is the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  31,10,"He created the heavens without any pillars that you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>can see, and cast firm mountains into the earth lest it sway with you, and scattered throughout it all kinds of treading creatures. And from the sky We sent down water, and We germinated therein many noble kinds of plants."
  31,11,"Such is Allah’s creation, so show<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>me what those apart from Him have created; rather, the unjust are in evident misguidance."
